rewrite Axi_r/wDatapump to support any alignment and transaction format.

* The functionality of these component is simple. Read or write any data
  from or to AXI bus while using most simple hardware do so.

* However the components do support Axi3, Axi4,
  Axi3Lite, Axi4Lite and other AMBA AXI variants. This means that there
  are diametrically different methods for counting of transaction words
  depending on bus interface used. The same applies to handling
  of the transaction id. The different combinations of transaction sizes
  and bus width do add an extra level of complexity.
  This level of complexity is increased even further by alignment logic
  which may require to cut/append some extra words in the transaction
  to cope for the alignment requirements. In addition
  the alignment could be static or dynamically specified by address
  (including the combinations). All posibilities are analyzed compile
  time and the not required combinations are not generated.
  Note that input information for optimisations is specified using user
  provided data type meta.

* Every frame spliting/merging, data/address alignment
  logic in this component is generated on demand. This means that
  this component may spot just a simple wires but may also spot
  a complex shift logic with a complicated check for word/max frame len
  crossing due to alignment or request size.

OutOfOrderCummulativeOp: write history based on trans. cnt. not latency

* write history was intendet to be used for compensation of latency
  of write -> read in main memory, however the previous implementation
  did understand this latency as a number of clocks,
  in this implementation it is interpreted as a number of transactions
  instead, this is more efficient as we can make this history smaller
  because the hazards are precisely acknowledged using handshake
